me":"Ferris","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Ó Fearghuis</b> or <b>Ó Fearghasa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fearghus</i>’, or from the Scottish-Gaelic form of this personal name, <i>Fearghus</i> (see   Fergus  ).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Ferrières-Saint-Hilaire, Eure and Ferrières, La Manche in Normandy, France."]},{"name":"Ferridge","meanings":["English: unexplained; possibly a form of  <i>Ferris</i> and therefore a variant of   Ferrers  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":30,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Joan de Ferrers was born in 1229, in Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, England. She married Thomas Lloyd in 1243, in Thurston, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1275, in her hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1229–1275":"1229–1275","1224–Male":"1224–Surnud","1227–1275":"1227–1275","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1249–1312":"1249–1312","1249":"1249","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","about 1249":"umbes 1249","1275":"1275","about 1244":"umbes 1244","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1229":"1229","Shabbington, Buckinghamshire":"Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, England":"Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, England","Bishops Castle, Okeley, Shropshire, England":"Bishop's Castle, Shropshire, England","Thurston, Suffolk, England":"Thurston, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1229–1275":"1229–1275","1224–Male":"1224–Kuollut","1227–1275":"1227–1275","1244–Female":"1244–Kuollut","1249–1312":"1249–1312","1249":"1249","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1312":"1312","1224":"1224","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","about 1249":"noin 1249","1275":"1275","about 1244":"noin 1244","about 1275":"noin 1275","1229":"1229","Shabbington, Buckinghamshire":"Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shabbington, Buckinghamshire, England":"Shabbington